<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06116215 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06116215 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Dodd  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  FAMILY; DISASTER; EMPLOYMENT; LEGISLATION; US; CONGRESS  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Renewing their challenge to President Bush, Senate Democrats on Wednesdayresurrected a bill granting 12 weeks of unpaid leave to workers with familyemergencies -- a measure Bush vetoed last year.;    The bill has become aprime symbol of the Democrats' differences with the Republican White House andis part of a package of domestic issues that Democratic candidates intend tofeature in national elections next year.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FAMILY LEAVE BILL REVIVED IN SENATEDEMOCRATS PUSH IT AS ELECTION ISSUE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., the bill's author, said Wednesday that hehad detected a slight softening of Republican resistance to the measure, andhe held out hope that Bush would reconsider his opposition.;    But Dodd alsoacknowledged that Democrats saw a chance to score political points with thelegislation.;    &quot;George Bush is going to have a family leave bill on his deskevery year that he's in office until he signs one,&quot; he said.;    12 weeks ayear;  The bill, approved 12-5 by the Senate Education and Labor Committee,would require companies employing more than 50 people to provide workers withup to 12 weeks of unpaid leave a year to care for a new child or a sick familymember. Employers would have to continue health benefits for workers on leaveand give them back their old jobs, or comparable ones, when they returned.;   The bill passed the Senate by voice vote last year and the House by acomfortable margin. But Bush vetoed it, and the House fell 54 votes short ofthe two-thirds majority needed to override.;    Veto threat renewed;  The vetothreat was renewed two weeks ago by Labor Secretary Lynn Martin, who was anardent supporter of the bill last year while serving as a Republican Congressmember from Illinois.;    Two Senate committee Republicans, Dan Coats ofIndiana and James Jeffords of Vermont, voted with the panel's 10 Democrats tosend the bill to the floor this year. Jeffords had voted for it before, butCoats switched sides this year.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  DAVID HESS, Mercury News Washington Bureau  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910425  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  327  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday April 25, 199100116215,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>